 For typesetting a piecewise-defined function with the given constraints in LaTeX, both the `cases` environment and an `array` can be used, but each has its advantages and disadvantages.

The `cases` environment, provided by the `amsmath` package, offers a convenient and easy-to-use solution:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}
\[
f(x) = \begin{cases}
  f_1(x), & x \in A \\
  f_2(x), & x \in B, \; x > c \\
  f_3(x), & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]
\end{document}
```

